# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: api-security-testing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:api-security-testing/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:api-security-testing/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:api-security-testing/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:api-security-testing/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:api-security-testing/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:api-security-testing/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:api-security-testing/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:api-security-testing/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:api-security-testing/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:api-security-testing/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:api-security-testing/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:api-security-testing/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:api-security-testing/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:api-security-testing/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:api-security-testing/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:api-security-testing/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:api-security-testing/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:api-security-testing/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:api-security-testing/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:api-security-testing/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:api-security-testing/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:api-security-testing/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:api-security-testing/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:api-security-testing/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:api-security-testing/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:api-security-testing/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:api-security-testing/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:api-security-testing/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:api-security-testing/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:api-security-testing/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:api-security-testing/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:api-security-testing/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:api-security-testing/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:api-security-testing/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:api-security-testing/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:api-security-testing/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:api-security-testing/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:api-security-testing/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] REST (or **RE**presentational **S**tate **T**ransfer) is an architectural style first described in Roy Fielding's Ph.D. dissertation on Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It evolved as Fielding wrote the HTTP/1.1 and URI specs and has been proven to be well-suited for developing distributed hypermedia applications.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] While REST is more widely applicable, it is most commonly used within the context of communicating with services via HTTP.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The key abstraction of information in REST is a resource.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A REST API resource is identified by a URI, usually a HTTP URL.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] REST components use connectors to perform actions on a resource by using a representation to capture the current or intended state of the resource and transferring that representation.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The primary connector types are client and server, secondary connectors include cache, resolver and tunnel.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Stateful APIs do not adhere to the REST architectural style.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] State in the REST acronym refers to the state of the resource which the API accesses, not the state of a session within which the API is called.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] While there may be good reasons for building a stateful API, it is important to realize that managing sessions is complex and difficult to do securely.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] In order to implement flows with REST APIs, resources are typically created, read, updated and deleted.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] For example, an ecommerce site may offer methods to create an empty shopping cart, to add items to the cart and to check out the cart.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Each of these REST calls is stateless and the endpoint should check whether the caller is authorized to perform the requested operation.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another key feature of REST applications is the use of standard HTTP verbs and error codes in the pursuit or removing unnecessary variation among different services.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another key feature of REST applications is the use of HATEOAS or Hypermedia As The Engine of Application State.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This provides REST applications a self-documenting nature making it easier for developers to interact with a REST service without prior knowledge.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Secure REST services must only provide HTTPS endpoints.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This protects authentication credentials in transit, for example passwords, API keys or JSON Web Tokens.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It also allows clients to authenticate the service and guarantees integrity of the transmitted data.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See the Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet for additional information.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Consider the use of mutually authenticated client-side certificates to provide additional protection for highly privileged web services.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Non-public REST services must perform access control at each API endpoint.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Web services in monolithic applications implement this by means of user authentication, authorization logic and session management.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This has several drawbacks for modern architectures which compose multiple microservices following the RESTful style.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] There seems to be a convergence towards using JSON Web Tokens (JWT) as the format for security tokens.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] JWTs are JSON data structures containing a set of claims that can be used for access control decisions.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A cryptographic signature or message authentication code (MAC) can be used to protect the integrity of the JWT.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] If MACs are used for integrity protection, every service that is able to validate JWTs can also create new JWTs using the same key.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This means that all services using the same key have to mutually trust each other.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another consequence of this is that a compromise of any service also compromises all other services sharing the same key.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The relying party or token consumer validates a JWT by verifying its integrity and claims contained.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Some claims have been standardized and should be present in JWT used for access controls.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] As JWTs contain details of the authenticated entity (user etc.) a disconnect can occur between the JWT and the current state of the users session, for example, if the session is terminated earlier than the expiration time due to an explicit logout or an idle timeout.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] When an explicit session termination event occurs, a unique, server-issued identifier (the `jti` claim, optionally combined with `aud`) should be submitted to a denylist on the API which will invalidate that JWT for any requests until the expiration of the token.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See the JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet for further details.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Public REST services without access control run the risk of being farmed leading to excessive bills for bandwidth or compute cycles.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] API keys can be used to mitigate this risk.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] They are also often used by organisation to monetize APIs; instead of blocking high-frequency calls, clients are given access in accordance to a purchased access plan.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] API keys can reduce the impact of denial-of-service attacks.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, when they are issued to third-party clients, they are relatively easy to compromise.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] In Java EE in particular, this can be difficult to implement properly.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See Bypassing Web Authentication and Authorization with HTTP Verb Tampering for an explanation of this common misconfiguration.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Modern REST APIs often implement business workflows through a sequence of endpoints (for example, create → validate → approve → finalize).
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] If the backend does not explicitly validate workflow state transitions, attackers may invoke endpoints out of sequence to bypass intended controls.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Because each endpoint may be individually authenticated and authorized, traditional access control checks often fail to detect these issues.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A REST request or response body should match the intended content type in the header.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Otherwise this could cause misinterpretation at the consumer/producer side and lead to code injection/execution.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It is common for REST services to allow multiple response types (e.g.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] `application/xml` or `application/json`, and the client specifies the preferred order of response types by the Accept header in the request.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] JavaScript) in their responses must be especially careful to defend against header injection attack.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] There are a number of security related headers that can be returned in the HTTP responses to instruct browsers to act in specific ways.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, some of these headers are intended to be used with HTML responses, and as such may provide little or no security benefits on an API that does not return HTML.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Note that if the API is only consumed by non-browser clients (e.g. mobile apps, server-to-server calls, command-line tools), most of these headers will have no effect since they are directives for browsers.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The headers below are only intended to provide additional security when responses are rendered as HTML.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] As such, if the API will **never** return HTML in responses, then these headers may not be necessary.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, if there is any uncertainty about the function of the headers, or the types of information that the API returns (or may return in future), then it is recommended to include them as part of a defence-in-depth approach.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is a W3C standard to flexibly specify what cross-domain requests are permitted.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] By delivering appropriate CORS Headers your REST API signals to the browser which domains, AKA origins, are allowed to make JavaScript calls to the REST service.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] RESTful web services should be careful to prevent leaking credentials.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Passwords, security tokens, and API keys should not appear in the URL, as this can be captured in web server logs, which makes them intrinsically valuable.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] `https://example.com/controller/123/action?apiKey=a53f435643de32` because the apiKey is in the URL.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] When designing REST API, don't just use `200` for success or `404` for error.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Always use the semantically appropriate status code for the response.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Here is a non-exhaustive selection of security related REST API **status codes**.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Use it to ensure you return the correct code.
[src:api-security-testing/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Additional information about HTTP return code usage in REST API can be found here and here.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Along the ease of API integSeemadifficulties of ensuring proper authentication (AuthN) and authorization (AuthZ).
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] In a multitenant environment, security controls based on proper AuthN and AuthZ can help ensure that API access is limited to those who need (and are entitled to) it.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Appropriate AuthN schemes enable producers (APIs or services) to properly identify consumers (clients or calling programs), and to evaluate their access level (AuthZ).
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] In other words, may a consumer invoke a particular method (business logic) based on the credentials presented?
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Dynamic tokens: These are time based tokens obtained by caller from an authentication service.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] User-delegated tokens: These are tokens such as OAuth which are granted based on user authentication.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Policy & attribute-based access control: policies use attributes to define how APIs can be invoked using standards such as ALFA or XACML.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] The above methods provide different level of security and ease of integration.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Oftentimes, the easiest method of integration also offers weakest security model.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] In static strings method, the API caller or client embeds a string as a token in the request.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] This method is often referred as basic authentication.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] "From a security point of view, basic authentication is not very satisfactory.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] It means sending the user's password over the network in clear text for every single page accessed (unless a secure lower-level protocol, like SSL, is used to encrypt all transactions).
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] When an API is protected by a dynamic token, there is a time-based nonce inserted into the token.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] The token has a time to live (TTL) after which the client must acquire a new token.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] The API method has a time check algorithm, and if the token is expired, the request is forbidden.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] "An example of such token is JSON Web Token.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] This type of token is used in three-legged systems where an application needs to access an API on behalf of a user.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] Instead of revealing user id and password to the application, a user grants a token which encapsulates users permission for the application to invoke the API.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] In this approach, there is a Policy Enforcement Point either within the API itself, in the API framework (as an interceptor or message handler), or as an API gateway (e.g.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] WSO2, Kong, Tyk, or similar) that intercepts the call to the API and / or the response back from the API.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] It converts it into an authorization request (typically in XACML) which it sends to a Policy Decision Point (PDP).
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] The Policy Decision Point is configured with policies that implement dynamic access control that can use any number of user, resource, action, and context attributes to define which access is allowed or denied.
[src:api-security-testing/web-api-security] 4. a relationship (e.g. the customer to whom the account belongs).
